with Old French <i>coudraie</i> ‘hazel copse’ (a collective noun from <i>coudre</i> ‘hazelnut tree’, Late Latin <i>colurus</i>, a metathesized form of classical Latin <i>corylus</i>, from Greek <i>korylos</i>). Alternatively, but less likely, a topographic name from Old French <i>coudraie</i> ‘hazel copse’, adopted into English, denoting someone who lived near a hazel copse."],"variants":[{"name":"Cowdery","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): variant of   Cowdrey  ."]}]},{"name":"Sir","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From Old Norse, originally a byname meaning ‘bride, wife’; in mythology the name of Thor's golden-haired wife."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Sir Robert de Cowdrey was born in 1390. He married Mrs Robert de Cowdrey before 1420, in England. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died in 1427, at the age of 37."},"et":{"1390–1427":"1390–1427","–Female":"Surnud","1420–1499":